---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import NeoCard from '../../components/NeoCard.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Deep Learning - AI/ML Hub">
  <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding-bottom: 5rem;">
    
    <!-- Hero Block -->
    <header class="neo-border neo-shadow bg-violet" style="padding: 2.5rem 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 3rem; text-align: center; border-width: 3.5px; background-color: #e9d5ff;">
      <span style="font-size: 3rem; display: block; margin-bottom: 1rem;">🧠</span>
      <h1 style="font-size: 2.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0; letter-spacing: -1px; line-height: 1;">Deep Learning</h1>
      <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: bold; color: #1f2937; margin: 0;">
        Representation learning through layered hierarchical neural architectures.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2.5rem;">
      
      <!-- Core ANN Concept -->
      <section class="neo-border" style="background-color: #fff; padding: 2rem; border-width: 3px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          The Artificial Neuron & Non-Linear Activation
        </h2>
        <p style="font-size: 1rem; font-weight: bold; color: #374151; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0 0 1.5rem 0;">
          An artificial neuron represents a basic computational node. It takes multiple inputs <code>xᵢ</code>, multiplies them by weights <code>wᵢ</code>, adds a bias <code>b</code>, and passes the aggregate through an activation function <code>f(z)</code>.
        </p>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="background: #a8d5ff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0;">Why Non-Linearity?</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: bold; color: #374151; line-height: 1.4; margin: 0;">
              If we don't apply a non-linear activation function, multiple layers of linear combinations would mathematically collapse back into a single linear function: 
              <code>W₂·(W₁·x + b₁) + b₂ = W'·x + b'</code>. 
              Non-linear activation functions allow neural networks to act as <strong>Universal Function Approximators</strong>, mapping arbitrary complex, curved, high-dimensional boundaries.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #bbf7d0; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0;">Activation Functions</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: bold; color: #374151; line-height: 1.4; margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
              <strong>ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit):</strong> <code>f(x) = max(0, x)</code>. Extremely simple, fast, and effectively mitigates the vanishing gradient problem in deep networks.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: bold; color: #374151; line-height: 1.4; margin: 0;">
              <strong>Softmax:</strong> Converts a vector of raw scores into probability distributions that sum to 1. Placed in the final layer for multi-class classification.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Backprop Card -->
      <NeoCard color="#a8d5ff" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          Mechanics: Propagation & Backpropagation
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          How networks learn. Gradient vectors flow forwards to compute loss, and backwards to distribute correction pressures.
        </p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Forward Propagation & Cost</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              Input features are fed into the input layer. Operations roll forward layer by layer (dot products + activations) until a prediction vector is computed at the output layer. 
              The prediction is compared to the ground truth label using a **Cost Function** (e.g. Mean Squared Error or Categorical Cross-Entropy) to calculate a single loss value representing the total error.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Backpropagation (The Engine of AI)</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              To minimize the loss, we need the gradient of the loss function with respect to every weight in the network. 
              Starting from the output layer, we calculate the local derivative of loss. 
              We then propagate this error backward using the <strong>Chain Rule</strong>, multiplying local partial derivatives step-by-step. 
              This tells us exactly how much a change in a weight in layer 1 will affect the final output error, letting us update weights: 
              <code>W = W - η·∇W</code>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- Architectures Card -->
      <NeoCard color="#fca5a5" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          Specialized Neural Architectures
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          Different data domains demand different inductive biases. Here are the two pillars of deep vision and sequence processing.
        </p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">CNNs (Convolutional Neural Networks) for Vision</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              Vision data is translation invariant (a cat is a cat whether it's in the top-left or bottom-right). 
              Instead of fully connected layers, CNNs use **Convolutions** (sliding filters/kernels over the pixel space) to compute spatial feature maps. 
              Followed by **Max-Pooling** to reduce dimensions and build invariance, CNNs build a hierarchy of features: first layers find edges, middle layers find shapes, and deep layers find complex objects.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">RNNs & LSTMs for Sequence Modeling</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              Text, speech, and time-series have sequential dependencies. **Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs)** preserve temporal loops, passing a hidden state vector along sequential tokens. 
              Because raw RNNs suffer from vanishing gradients over long sequences, **LSTMs (Long Short-Term Memory)** introduce a linear "cell state" pathway managed by three interactive mathematical gates (forget gate, input gate, output gate) to write, read, and preserve long-term context safely!
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- Roadmap Back Home -->
      <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a href="/domains/machine-learning" class="neo-border bg-green neo-hover-raise" style="padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: #000; text-decoration: none; border-width: 3px; background-color: #bbf7d0; box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #000;">
          &larr; Machine Learning
        </a>
        <a href="/domains/generative-ai" class="neo-border bg-yellow neo-hover-raise" style="padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: #000; text-decoration: none; border-width: 3px; background-color: #fef08a; box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #000;">
          Generative AI &rarr;
        </a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
